# Key Assumptions of the Paper

Assumption 1

Assumption:
Base classifiers are drawn from a finite hypothesis space.

Why the method needs it:
The theoretical bounds depend on the size of the hypothesis space.
 
Violation scenario:
If the hypothesis space is extremely large or infinite, the bound becomes loose.

Paper reference:
Theoretical analysis section.

--------------------------------

Assumption 2

Assumption:
Training examples are independently drawn from a distribution.

Why the method needs it:
Theoretical guarantees rely on i.i.d sampling.

Violation scenario:
Time series datasets where samples are dependent.

Paper reference:
Section describing distribution D.

--------------------------------

Assumption 3

Assumption:
Base classifiers output binary labels (-1, +1).

Why the method needs it:
Margin definition depends on binary predictions.

Violation scenario:
If classifiers output probabilities instead of binary labels.

Paper reference:
Base hypothesis definition.
